This isn't correct.

Almost all Firewire drives are bootable. The ones that aren't
bootable are really rare, especially if they're newer models. I have
booted successfully with drives that use: Oxford, Initio, Indigita,
Prolific, LSI Logic, TI, and VIA chipsets, as well as unidentified
chipsets shown in System Profiler as Maxtor and Seagate (this is set
by custom the firmware they use, and isn't the real manufacturer of
the chipset, which would have to be visually inspected to determine
the maker).

The only chipset I've ever used that wouldn't boot was the early
Prolific PL-3507 Rev.A used in the Ultra Mini Disk and other older,
and very inexpensive enclosures. Also, Genesys Logic chipsets can
boot, but they are designed wrong and have an error that  will
corrupt data on any Firewire connection - Mac or PC - they should
never be used, and be recycled rather than resold.
