I am skeptical of an article posted as a &quot;blog&quot; that has many claims
against all cloning tools EXCEPT SuperDuper (SD). If you read the
reasons that different products are given failing marks, and then
research this yourself, I think you'll find this author's claims are
not credible.

For example, in the critique of Carbon Copy Cloner (CCC) one of the
claims against CCC is that &quot;creation dates&quot; are not preserved. I have
a HD cloned with CCC and also have the original. I searched through
both drives comparing creation dates, and found zero instances in
which a creation date was not preserved. I believe this claim about
not preserving creation dates with CCC to be untrue.

Further, some of the metadata attributes are not even functional, for
instance, ACLs (Access Control Lists) which every single cloning tool
other than SD fails to preserve are not even used in any current OS X
System, and to be utilized at all must first be &quot;enabled&quot; for each
volume. To my knowledge, none of us would have these &quot;enabled&quot;, so
this is a total red herring. I'm also skeptical of the claim that
these aren't preserved by other tools, but since I do not have these
enable, and they aren't being utilized, I have no way to confirm my
suspicion.

I think the blog article claiming how much better SD is than all
others is likely disinformation, and close scrutiny of the claims
will show that for the most part they're false. That's not to say
that SD isn't a good tool. All that I'm saying is that the claims of
the author either appear to be false in some instances, or not
relevant to producing working, bootable, functional clones.

Whenever I read extraordinary claims, I expect extraordinary
evidence. When the evidence appears to be lacking, I cynically fall
back on the premise of &quot;who benefits&quot; and &quot;follow the money&quot;. In this
case, Super Duper benefits, and Super Duper gets the money, so that's
two strikes against Super Duper. The false claims in the article seem
to be a third strike, so even if Super Duper is indeed the very best
cloning tool, I recoil from the blog article that slants the truth so
heavily in favor of Super Duper.

My reality is that I've produced perfectly functional clones using
both CCC and Disk Utility, which are both free, and to my knowledge
I've never experienced any shortcoming that was cited in this biased,
misleading, and perhaps purposefully untruthful blog article.
